Module 7 :

Application Load Balancer (ALB)

Open AWS Load Balancer:
Open the EC2 Dashboard.
Navigate to Load Balancers under Load Balancing.
Reason: The Load Balancer distributes incoming traffic across multiple EC2 instances, improving availability and performance.
Create a Target Group (Before Creating the Load Balancer):
Click Target Groups.
Reason: A Target Group tells the Load Balancer which EC2 instances should receive incoming requests.
Click Create Target Group:
Reason: Creates a logical group of backend EC2 instances.
Choose Target Type: Instances
Reason: Traffic will be routed directly to EC2 instances.
Set Protocol: HTTP
Reason: The web application communicates over the HTTP protocol.
Set Port: 8000:
Reason: The application running on the EC2 instances listens on Port 8000.
Select Your VPC:
Reason: The Target Group must belong to the same VPC as the EC2 instances.
Enter Target Group Name
Reason: A meaningful name helps identify the Target Group easily.

Click Next

Reason: Proceed to register backend EC2 instances.
Register Targets:

Select the two public EC2 instances:
Do NOT select the Bastion Host.
Reason: Only the application servers should receive user traffic. The Bastion Host is used only for SSH access.
Click Include as Pending Below
Reason: Registers the selected EC2 instances with the Target Group.
Click Create Target Group
Reason: Completes the Target Group configuration.
Create the Application Load Balancer
Go back to Load Balancers.
Click Create Load Balancer.
Choose Application Load Balancer.
Reason: An Application Load Balancer distributes HTTP/HTTPS traffic across multiple backend servers.
Enter Load Balancer Name:
Reason: Makes it easier to identify the Load Balancer.
Scheme: Internet-facing
Reason: Allows users on the internet to access the application.
IP Address Type: IPv4
Reason: Provides IPv4 connectivity for client requests.
Select the VPC:
Choose the same VPC used by the EC2 instances.
Reason: The Load Balancer and Target Group must be in the same VPC.
Select Availability Zones:
Choose two Availability Zones.
Select Public Subnets:
Reason: Using multiple Availability Zones improves high availability and fault tolerance.
Select the Security Group:
Choose the previously created Load Balancer Security Group.
Reason: The Security Group controls inbound and outbound traffic to the Load Balancer.
Configure Listener
Protocol: HTTP
Port: 80
Forward requests to the created Target Group.
Reason: The Listener receives client requests and forwards them to the Target Group.
Review Configuration
Verify all settings.
Click Create Load Balancer:
Reason: Creates the Application Load Balancer.
Verify the Load Balancer
